            <p>
                Even if callers listen to the entire message, they <strong>cannot book immediately</strong>. The momentum dies. They have to switch contexts (call → wait → callback → book), and in that gap, competitors with online booking capture them.
            </p>
            <div class="stat">77% of clients prefer booking online vs. phone</div>
        </div>

        <div class="pain-point">
            <h3><span style="font-size: 20px; margin-right: 8px;">🌙</span> After-Hours Dead End</h3>
            <p>
                <strong>55% of booking intent happens when the shop is closed</strong>—evenings, early mornings, weekends. Your voicemail helps with info, but these high-intent clients <strong>cannot convert</strong>. They'll find a competitor whose website lets them book at 11 PM for tomorrow morning.
            </p>
            <div class="stat">30% of bookings happen 5 PM - 9 PM (after close)</div>
        </div>

        <div class="pain-point">
            <h3><span style="font-size: 20px; margin-right: 8px;">💬</span> The Callback Bottleneck</h3>
            <p>
                Of the 20% who leave messages, you must call back during business hours—when <strong>you're cutting hair</strong>. This creates delays. By the time you return the call, they've often booked elsewhere or lost interest.
            </p>
